<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-488-320  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 488 320.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  July 27 1989 v37 n16 p61(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Operate an LCD display from a VGA system. (liquid crystal display;video graphics array)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johary, Arun; Oguchi, T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>LCDs are capable of meeting all the requirements of a laptopcomputer, including small size, low power, high contrast and largeviewing angle.andP;  Liquid crystal material is particularly flexible,but it is protected by two parallel plain-glass plates at thecenter of an LCD panel.andP;  LCD material is divided into a largenumber of separate cells or pixels by an electrode matrix on theglass plates.andP;  A VGA panel requires 640 row electrodes along itsleft vertical edge and 480 column electrodes along its tophorizontal edge.andP;  Different voltages applied to the row and columnelectrodes control the electric fields across the pixels, an LCDscanning scheme similar to the raster scanning of a CRT.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   IBM Video Graphics Array (Circuit board) (equipment and supplies).andO;Topic:     Liquid Crystal DisplaysPixelsControllersHigh ResolutionLaptop Computers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Center of an LCD panel. (chart)High-resolution LCD panel configuration. (chart)Low-resolution display mode on a high-resolution screen. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>